data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new **span overload resolution rules**. Your `array.Contains(num)` now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so this throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` (or use `.AsEnumerable()`) to force binding to `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches ensure the expression tree uses the `Enumerable.Contains` overload, which is representable in expression trees. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` version returning `void`).
